lbladder stones:\nStones in ultrasound appear as\nechogenic structures with acoustic\nshadow\nComputed tomography (CT)\n1. CT is the gold standard imaging modalities in GIT emergencies.\n2. Rapid and non-invasive.\n3. Multiplanar reconstruction (axial, coronal and sagittal) improves accuracy of\nreporting.\n4. Generally not portable\n5. Exposes patient to moderate dose of ionizing radiation.\n6. Intravenous contrast should be administered to improve sensitivity of the test for\nsolid organ injury and vessel injury.\n7. Multiphasic scan is the accurate form of imaging (for the diagnosis or exclusion of\nvascular injury or active intra-abdominal hemorrhage). This may include all or\nsome of the following phases: non-contrast, arterial, portal venous. A 5–10 min\ndelayed urographic phase can be performed if urinary tract injury is suspected\nclinically.\n90"}